"MAY YOU NEVER HAVE TO BURY YOUR CHILD."

Marked by the baby’s IV drip, Apteri stands next to the grave of her two week old daughter, in the corner of her now abandoned goat pen.

Apteri was unable to produce milk to breastfeed her baby due to health complications caused by the stress of having to sell her last remaining goat, which was her only source of income.

..........................................

Our “MAY YOU…” project came about as a reaction to my last trip to the Horn of Africa, with @concernworldwideus, where the region is enduring the worst drought in 40 years.  As we left conversations with people, they would say, “May your family be blessed.”

I was constantly shocked that these people, who had nothing, least of all hope, were able to find it in their hearts to bless a fellow human being.  It highlighted to me that we ARE all connected, and I started to think about other blessings that we would all want to wish upon our fellow brothers and sisters.

If you are able, please donate what you can at the link in my bio. Thank you. X

En route from NYC - LA, got diverted to Phoenix, AZ due to blizzards in LA.

Now walking the midnight empty hallways of Pheonix Airport, waiting for next flight out, which won't be for 9 hours, with the knowledge that I'm supposed to be on set in 5 hours.

Always interesting to watch the different personalities around me in these situations:

-"The Ragers". Those who just won't accept the situation and have to throw their anger at whomever they can (the airline staff usually get the brunt of it)

-"The Pessimists". The people who love to say "I knew this would happen", almost happy to have their negative thoughts validated.

-"The Defiant Ones". The ones who, despite being told there are no flights, nor hotels, still try and beat the system (and who, after all their efforts, end up on the same delayed flight as everyone else.)

-"The Surfers". Those who calmly ride the wave and make the best of the bad situation, with the knowledge that there is nothing they can do but stay calm and ride it out.

For better or worse, I am the "Surfer" type. Either because I am naturally zen about everything OR because I am emotionally incapable of handling stress, so being zen is my only option ;)... Also, one of my morning mantras is "Thank you for the knowledge that everything that happens to me is for my best possible outcome"... which helps in seeing each situation from a different perspective. 

Found a corner to spend the night. Big gratitude for the carpet (I have slept on the shiny hard airport floor a few times... not fun) and my eye mask :) 

Stay loose dude.

Covering @amazingmagazine spring/summer 2023 issue, Conversations with Friends star Jemima Kirke discusses her role in new Apple TV+ drama City on Fire, which was adapted from Garth Risk Hallberg’s 2015 novel of the same name.

“I don't consider [the book], and that's not for laziness or disinterest, I just don't think it's relevant,” says Kirke, on bringing a book character to life on screen. “I'll read the book if I want to, and I did read Conversations with Friends because I heard a lot of chatter about Sally Rooney, who I hadn't heard of at that point and so I wanted to see what the fuss was about. I really enjoyed the book, but it is an adaptation, it’s a piece of work that is using the book as a source material. It’s helpful to the writers and I did get a sense for Conversations with Friends of who they wanted Melissa to be before I auditioned. You only get so many pages for an audition and so you have to go off something. Doing an audition is like being on a game show where they never tell you whether you've got the answer right or not, so the more information you can get, the better.”

City on Fire begins streaming on 12 May on @appletv . For Jemima’s interview and shoot, order your copy of AMAZING issue 3 at www.theamazingmagazine.com now.

Yesterday I photographed @alexilubomirski . As much as I can try to pretend that it wasn’t a big deal- it was, to be honest, I hardly could sleep the night before. Taking a picture of a handsome man is not a challenge but photographing one of the most famous photographers can be intimidating. As there was no school yesterday, Maya went with me to assist. Best day of my life; having my girl with me when doing what I love- that’s how I want my life to be every day. In Mays’s words :”he is super nice, doesn’t know much about snakes but can learn and he gets extra points for wanting to be a poet”. When I was editing my pictures I was thinking to remove myself from the background but Maya said NO, you are both photographers you should be there so… I am. Thank you Alexi, you made my day (more like you made my month!)

A x

So yesterday was my birthday and this little lady gave me a gift. 

We adopted her about 2.5 weeks ago from @rescuecity.  She immediately took to my wife and sons but seemed scared of me. If I went towards her too fast or with no one else around, she would back nervously into a corner or simply run away. 

If the kids were playing with her outside and she seemed to be having fun, if I tried to join in, she would run inside. 

When I hugged my sons, she would come up and put her paw on my sons, almost trying to protect them from me. 

I would try and go on the ground and give her a little love, but with little luck. 

One day, a man came over to drop off something, and again, the dog backed away from him. The man immediately said that he had animals that were rescues and that he himself had a horse that had been abused and that would never let him hug it, but if the wife tried, it would allow her.

He said that the dog may have had a male figure that had abused it or, at the very least, was mean to it. 

So I told our dog that there was no rush at all and whenever she was ready, I would be there.

Yesterday, I woke up early before the kids and had a little birthday exercise and meditation. As I finished the meditation, she came in and got up on the sofa next to me. 

I put my hand on her paw, and she licked it and then put her other paw on top of my hand. 

We stayed there for a while before one of my sons bounded in.

She even let me throw a ball for her yesterday and gave me a few kisses.

Bit by bit, we are getting there.

Anyone for a little afternoon Novak? :)

I was commissioned to shoot a classic portrait of Mr. Lauren for @harpersbazaarus in London. 

Mr. Lauren did his usual perfect pose with a slight grin.

I asked him if I could put some music on. 

"Sure," he repiled. 

I put on some Frank Sinatra, and all of a sudden, a glint appeared in Mr. Lauren's eyes as he started clicking his fingers.

Then, to the shock of everyone on set, Mr. Lauren glided to the side and started dancing across the room like Fred Astaire. 

I looked over my shoulder at his team, who were all half smiling, half in shock, and I just pressed the shutter as many times as possible before the song finished. 

"I think you've got the shot," he said, as the song faded out, shaking my hand and walking off set.
